NBA Regular Season Win Prediction

require(tidyr)
require(ggplot2)
require(dplyr)
require(randomForest)
require(gbm)

Background

In the NBA, the best regular season record doesnt necessarily promise a championship, but its still very important since it determines whether you advance and the seeding during the playoffs. Among the top 8 teams from each division (East and West), the team with the best record plays the team with the worst one. Therefore, teams with a better record (i.e., more regular season wins) are rewarded with a (usually) easier path to the championship. Beyond the obvious interest to basketball teams, betting markets offer the ability to bet the over/under on the number of wins each team will get in a regular season. For instance, will the Golden State Warriors win more or less than 67 games this season?

I was interested in investigating the following questions:

  1. Can a model accurately predict the number of regular season wins a team?
  2. What team statistics are most important for predicting number of wins?
  3. What is the best model to use between bagging, random forests, and boosting?

Dataset

Basketball-reference.com is a tremendous resource for all types of basketball statistics. My dataset consisted of regular season records for teams in the National Basketball Association (NBA) for the 2013-14 through 2017-18 regular season. There are 5 seasons and 30 teams, so there are 150 rows consisting of each teams record in each season. In addition, I included various Team Per Game Stats and Opponent Per Game Stats. For this analysis, I manually selected 16 variables: 3-point shot percentage, 2-point shot percentage, field goal percentage (i.e., both 2- and 3-point shots), free throw percentage, offensive rebounds, defensive rebounds, assists, steals, blocks, turnovers, personal fouls, points scored, points allowed, offensive rating, defensive rating, and pace of play.

This is because the Charlotte Bobcats rebranded as the Charlotte Hornets after the 2013-14 season. Therefore, I consolidated all instances of the team name as the Charlotte Hornets.

Scatterplot matrices can visualize the relationships between all variables simultaneously. In this case, I used it a little differently to see the relationship between number of wins and each of our team statistics independently. It is clear that offensive rating (ORtg) and defensive rating (DRtg) are positively correlated with number of wins. Also, points allowed (PTS_Allowed) has an expectedly negative correlation with number of wins, while points scored (PTS) has a positive but apparently weaker correlation. Finally, the shot efficiency metrics such as 2-point shot, 3-point shot, and field goal percentages had weak positive correlations as well.

Machine Learning Prediction of Wins

Training & Testing Sets

To facilitate modeling using our machine learning methods, we must split the data into independent training and testing sets. The training set will be used to build the models, while the testing set will be used to evaluate their performance and avoid overfitting on a single dataset. Data was randomly split into 70% training (n=105) and 30% testing (n=45) sets. Both sets had relatively similar numbers of wins (36 vs.41 wins on average).

final_df <- merged_df %>% select(-Team, -Season)

names(final_df) <- make.names(names(final_df))

set.seed(1)
train = sample(1:nrow(final_df), floor(nrow(final_df)*0.7))
#Training Set Wins
summary(final_df[train,"W"])
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    9.00   23.00   37.00   35.72   46.00   73.00
#Testing Set Wins
summary(final_df[-train,"W"])
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   10.00   25.00   41.00   37.73   50.00   62.00

For all analyses, number of wins per season was treated as the dependent variable and the 16 team statistics as the independent variables (predictors). Each technique will be done using 5000 trees. Bagging and random forests were done using the randomForest package, and boosting was done using the gbm package. Mean squared error (MSE) was used to evaluate accuracy of the model. ercentage increase in MSE (%IncMSE) if the given feature was removed from the model was used to rank its importance in bagging, random forest models, and boosting models.

Bagging

Bagging is a technique, where m samples are taken at random with replacement from a dataset and a tree fit to each random sample. Depending on the type of outcome variable - continuous or binary - the average or mode of the predictions of the m models becomes the final prediction. For bagging, the 5 most important variables according to %IncMSE were: points allowed (+24%), offensive rating (+20%), defensive rating (+14%), 3P% (+8%), and points scored (+8%).

bagging=randomForest(W~.,data=final_df,subset=train,mtry=(ncol(final_df)-1),importance=TRUE)

yhat.bag = predict(bagging,newdata=final_df[-train,])

varImpPlot(bagging)

Random Forests

Random forests are a special case of bagging, where only a random sample M of all available predictors (p) is available at each split in the tree. This aspect avoids overfitting by preventing any single predictor from constantly dominating all the trees. As a rule of thumb, the number of predictors at each split is p.

In the random forest model, the 5 most important variables according to %IncMSE if removed were: points allowed (+20%), offensive rating (+16%), defensive rating (+13%), field goal percentage (+7%) and 3-point percentage (+7%)

rf=randomForest(W~.,data=final_df,subset=train,mtry=sqrt(ncol(final_df)-1),importance=TRUE,ntree=500)

yhat.rf = predict(rf, newdata=final_df[-train,])

varImpPlot(rf)

Boosting

Boosting is a technique where an ensemble of trees is built sequentially, such that each subsequent tree is modeled to minimize the residual error terms from the previous trees. It relies on the idea that each individual tree will be a weak learner but combined all of the trees together become a strong learner that is less prone to overfitting. I selected a shrinkage parameter (\(\lambda\)) of 0.1, and set a maximum depth (d) of 4 layers per tree. In the boosting model, the 5 most important variables according to relative influence were: defensive rating (20), points allowed (16), offensive rating (14), 3-point percentage (9), and 2-point percentage (5)

boost=gbm(W~.,data=final_df[train,], distribution="gaussian", n.trees=5000, interaction.depth=4)

yhat.boost=predict(boost,newdata=final_df[-train,], n.trees=5000)

boostImp<-summary(boost, plotit = FALSE)
boostImp %>% ggplot(aes(x=reorder(var, rel.inf), y=rel.inf)) + geom_bar(stat = 'identity') + coord_flip() +
  labs(x="Statistic", y="Relative Influence (%IncMSE)")

Comparison

The MSE for number of wins was similar across all the algorithms:

  1. Bagging (MSE = 136)
  2. Random Forest (MSE = 137)
  3. Boosting (MSE = 136)
comp <- data.frame(Prediction = integer(135),
                   Actual = integer(135),
                   Method = character(135))
comp$Actual <- rep(test_set ,3)
comp$Prediction <- c(yhat.bag, yhat.rf, yhat.boost)
comp$Method <- c(rep("Bagging", length(yhat.bag)), rep("Random Forests", length(yhat.rf)), rep("Boosting", length(yhat.boost)))

comp %>% 
ggplot(aes(x=Actual, y=Prediction, color=Method)) + geom_point() + geom_abline(slope=1, intercept = 0, lty=2) + facet_wrap(Method~.) + labs(x="Actual Wins per Season", y="Predicted Wins per Season") + theme(legend.position="none")

Conclusion

A MSE of 136 means the models can predict a teams number of regular season record to within +/- 6 wins on average. Overall, there werent any major differences in the predictive ability of these algorithms using our specific dataset. Similarly, the top 5 most important variables were consistent across all models. The predictors that were always important were: offensive rating, defensive rating, points allowed, and 3 point percentage.

This is not surprising because offensive and defensive rating are proxies for efficiency as they try to estimate the number of points scored or allowed per 100 possessions, respectively. These advanced statistics aggregate the effects of many variables. For instance, offensive rating is calculated using a complex formula that includes free throws, field goals, assists, and the strength of the opponent played [1]. Also, defensive rating and/or points allowed appeared to be more important than offensive rating in predicting wins, which reinforces the common idea that defense wins games. Interestingly, 3-point percentage was consistently important for winning. In the modern era of basketball, data analytics has popularized the concept that a 3-point shot is worth more than a 2-point shot, despite being more difficult. The similar observation in this data may be reflective of this broader changing dynamic of the game and growing focus on the 3-point shot. Overall, the data seem to suggest teams that want to win should focus on improving their defense, 3-point shot and overall efficiency. Coaches should emphasize getting good scoring opportunities on offense and staying focused on defense.

Next Steps

  1. Incorporate more variables into the models. This may require some feature selection methods to avoid a problem with high dimensionality.
  2. Machine learning may work better if I use a larger sample size (i.e., data from more seasons). This is particularly important if I follow step #1 to avoid problems with high dimensionality.
  3. One of my motivating applications for this analysis was predicting the number of wins for betting markets. It would be interesting to investigate whether regular season statistics from the previous season can predict the win record in the next season.
